<tr>
<th>
Introduction to motivic homotopy theory
</th>
<td class="speaker">
<a href="https://sites.google.com/umich.edu/jackcarlisle">Jack Carlisle</a>
</td>
<td>August 1 - August 5</td>
<!-- <td>(M–F)</td> -->
<td>1 - 2:30</td>
<td>Zoom (link sent through email)</td>
<td style="text-align: center;"><button id="toggleAbstract9">Show</button></td>
<td style="text-align: center;"><!--<a href="http://www-personal.umich.edu/~willdana/RingelHallSlides.html"> <img src="minicourses2022_files/Adobe_PDF_file_icon_24x24.png" alt="PDF"> </a>--></td>
<td>  </td>
</tr>
<tr id="abstract9" class="abstract">
<td class="theAbstract" colspan="8">
<p><em>Abstract.</em> This mini-course will introduce participants to the basic definitions and constructions of motivic homotopy theory. We will pay special attention to complex and real motivic homotopy theory, which are intimately related to classical and C_2-equivariant stable homotopy theory. Basic knowledge of algebraic topology and algebraic geometry will be helpful, and all are encouraged to participate.
</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>

